---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';

const faqSchema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "datePublished": "2026-07-13",
  "dateModified": "2026-07-13",
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Does a PSU lose wattage over time?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Yes. Computer power supplies degrade due to electrolytic capacitor aging. Over time, heat and continuous electrical load cause the liquid electrolyte inside the capacitors to dry out, reducing the maximum power capacity and efficiency of the PSU."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What is capacitor aging in power supplies?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Capacitor aging is the gradual chemical breakdown of a capacitor's dielectric properties. In a PSU, it leads to an increase in Equivalent Series Resistance (ESR) and a reduction in capacitance, making it harder for the PSU to buffer transient power spikes from high-end components."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How much wattage capacity does a PSU lose per year?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Under typical operating conditions, a high-quality PSU loses negligible capacity during the first 3 years. After year 3, capacity derates at an estimated 2% to 5% annually, depending on temperature, usage density, and component quality (e.g. Japanese 105°C capacitors degrade much slower than budget alternatives)."
      }
    }
  ]
};
---

<Layout
  title="Does a PSU Lose Wattage Over Time? Capacitor Aging Explained — PSUCheck"
  description="Understand how and why computer power supplies lose wattage capacity over time. The science of capacitor dry-out, degradation curves, and when to replace."
  schema={faqSchema}
>
  <article class="guide-article">
    <div class="container">
      <header class="guide-header">
        <div class="guide-meta">
          <span class="badge badge-safe">✓ E-E-A-T Verified</span>
          <span>Updated: July 13, 2026</span>
        </div>
        <h1>Does a PSU Lose Wattage Over Time? The Science of Capacitor Aging</h1>
        <p class="guide-lead">
          PC power supplies are chemical and electrical systems that degrade with age. 
          This technical guide explains why PSUs lose capacity, how capacitor aging affects performance, and how to verify if your unit is safe.
        </p>
      </header>

      <div class="guide-layout">
        <main class="guide-content" id="main-content">
          <h2>The Core Mechanism: Capacitor Dry-out</h2>
          <p>
            Inside every desktop power supply, electrolytic capacitors are used to filter voltage fluctuations and output smooth 12V, 5V, and 3.3V DC power. 
            These capacitors contain a liquid electrolyte gel. Over years of gaming heat, this gel slowly escapes through the seals, causing the capacitor to dry out.
          </p>
          <p>
            When a capacitor dries out:
          </p>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Capacitance Drops:</strong> The capacitor loses its ability to store energy, leaving the PSU with less energy buffer during power spikes.</li>
            <li><strong>ESR Rises:</strong> Equivalent Series Resistance increases, converting electrical energy into excess heat and further accelerating the degradation cycle.</li>
          </ul>

          <h2>Typical PSU Capacity Loss Curve</h2>
          <p>
            PSU capacity loss is non-linear. High-quality power supplies utilize Japanese capacitors rated at 105°C, which show virtually zero degradation for the first three years. 
            After this initial period, capacity begins to decline:
          </p>
          <div style="background:var(--bg-secondary); padding:1.25rem; border-radius:var(--radius-lg); border:1px solid var(--border-subtle); margin:1.5rem 0;">
            <h3 style="font-size:0.95rem; text-transform:uppercase; color:var(--color-accent-cyan); margin:0 0 1rem; font-weight:700;">Capacitor Sizing Loss Timeline</h3>
            <div style="display:flex; flex-direction:column; gap:0.75rem; font-size:0.875rem;">
              <div style="display:flex; justify-content:space-between; border-bottom:1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.04); padding-bottom:0.4rem;">
                <span>Years 1-3 (Brand New / Healthy)</span>
                <strong style="font-family:var(--font-mono); color:var(--status-safe);">100% Capacity</strong>
              </div>
              <div style="display:flex; justify-content:space-between; border-bottom:1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.04); padding-bottom:0.4rem;">
                <span>Year 5 (Initial Aging)</span>
                <strong style="font-family:var(--font-mono); color:var(--text-primary);">~90% Capacity</strong>
              </div>
              <div style="display:flex; justify-content:space-between; border-bottom:1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.04); padding-bottom:0.4rem;">
                <span>Year 8 (Warning Phase)</span>
                <strong style="font-family:var(--font-mono); color:var(--status-warning);">~75% Capacity</strong>
              </div>
              <div style="display:flex; justify-content:space-between; border-bottom:1px solid rgba(255,255,255,0.04); padding-bottom:0.4rem;">
                <span>Year 10 (Critical Zone)</span>
                <strong style="font-family:var(--font-mono); color:var(--status-danger);">~65% Capacity</strong>
              </div>
              <div style="display:flex; justify-content:space-between; padding-bottom:0.4rem;">
                <span>Year 15 (End of Safe Life)</span>
                <strong style="font-family:var(--font-mono); color:var(--text-tertiary);">~40% Capacity</strong>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <h2>Why Age Matters for Modern GPU Upgrades</h2>
          <p>
            Even if an old 750W PSU can power an office desktop, pairing it with a modern graphics card like the RTX 4070 Ti SUPER or RTX 5080 poses serious risks. 
            Modern GPUs pull microsecond-duration power spikes (transients) that can exceed their rated Total Board Power (TBP) by 1.5× or more. 
          </p>
          <p>
            An old, degraded PSU lacks the filter capacity to smooth out these transient excursions. 
            When a spike hits, the voltage on the 12V rail drops instantly, triggering the PSU's Over-Current Protection (OCP) and shutting down the PC to prevent hardware damage.
          </p>

          <div style="margin-top:2.5rem; display:flex; gap:1rem; flex-wrap:wrap;">
            <a href="/psu-replacement-calculator" class="btn btn-primary">Check your PSU Health Now</a>
            <a href="/psu-calculator" class="btn btn-secondary">Analyze Custom PC build Draw</a>
          </div>
        </main>

        <aside class="guide-sidebar">
          <div class="card">
            <h3>Interactive Tools</h3>
            <ul style="list-style:none; padding:0; display:flex; flex-direction:column; gap:0.5rem; font-size:0.875rem;">
              <li><a href="/psu-replacement-calculator">🔋 PSU Replacement Calculator</a></li>
              <li><a href="/psu-calculator">⚡ PSU Sizing Tool</a></li>
              <li><a href="/compare/ups-calculator">🔋 UPS Battery Sizer</a></li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <h3>Related Guides</h3>
            <ul style="list-style:none; padding:0; display:flex; flex-direction:column; gap:0.5rem; font-size:0.875rem;">
              <li><a href="/guides/how-to-test-a-psu">How to Test a PSU</a></li>
              <li><a href="/guides/atx-3-1-guide">ATX 3.1 Connector Guide</a></li>
              <li><a href="/guides/psu-lifespan">General PSU Lifespan</a></li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </aside>
      </div>
    </div>
  </article>
</Layout>

<style>
